      <hedline>
        <hl1>For Environment's Sake, Recharge Your Electric Car at Night; Power Plant Problem</hl1>
      </hedline>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I applaud James Graham's idea for replaceable batteries in electric cars (Op-Ed Sept. 26).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I applaud James Graham's idea for replaceable batteries in electric cars (Op-Ed Sept. 26).</p>
        <p>However, the advantages of electric cars are not as great as they may seem. Electric cars are as clean as the power plant that produces the electricity to charge the batteries. Converting to electric cars would increase demand for electricity, resulting in higher prices, more power plants and increased pollution from the power plants.</p>
        <p>Although levels of hydrocarbons, carbon monoxide and nitrous oxides will decrease, the level of carbon dioxide will increase (at coal plants). Since the increase would occur at the sites of the power plants, outside the cities, air quality in cities would improve. Unfortunately, the rise in carbon dioxide may exacerbate global warming. RANDY SILVERS San Diego, Oct. 2, 1991</p>
      </block>
